Defining CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) \
CSS is a programming language used to describe the presentation of a document such as HTML. CSS is used to customize Layout, font, colour, positioning, space, sizing, transitions etc. and without having to completely changing the site content. [CSS allows separation of presentation and content.]\
\
Why would we use CSS? \
- Faster workflow and efficient because you can make changes across an entire webpage instead of editing a single element\
- Website speed as CSS manages decorative elements by reducing size and allows webpage to run more smooth\
- Can reorganize to suit the users screen and resolution eg. TV, computer\
- Flexibility: organizes elements in a way that ensures that they are appropriate for the device they are being viewed on.\
\
CSS applied to html \
\ul Inline Styling:\ulnone  directly applies changes using the <style> attribute \cf2 (***highest priority, may override other styling)\cf0 \
\ul Internal style:\ulnone  adding style element to the head section of the document. affects the entire page that it is applied.\cf2  (***second priority)  \cf0 \
\ul external styling:\ulnone  can be placed in a separate external file usually beside an html file. affects the entire document as a whole providing a more uniform visual concept to the webpage. \
