\f1\b CSS Selectors and Properties
\f0\b0 \
Selector is a pattern used to select the content or elements you want to style. \
Three types of selectors \
\ul Class selectors:\ulnone  allow to isolate and style groups of HTML elements based on their identified class \
syntax eg. \cf3  [full stop/period (.)] + [class name]\cf0 \
\cf3 <p class=\'93roboclass\'94>This paragraph will have the roboclass style.</p>\
<p> This paragraph WILL NOT have the roboclass style.</p> \cf4  (attribute syntax is not used) \cf0 \
class selector code structure eg. .\cf3 intro \{\
					color: silver; \
           				\}\cf0 \
\
\ul ID selectors : \ulnone allow to isolate a single HTML element based on their ID \
syntax eg. \cf3 [hash/pound (#)] + [ID name]. \
<h1 id=\'93idselector\'94> This paragraph WILL NOT have the idSElector style. </h1> \cf4 (due to CSS being case sensitive the ID selector would not be inherited by <h1>). \cf3 \
<h2 id=\'93idSelector\'94> This paragraph will have the roboclass style.</h2>\
\cf4 idSelector code structure eg.\cf3  #idSelector \{\
					background-colour: lightgreen; \
				    \} \cf4 \
\cf0 \
\ul Element selectors: \ulnone allows to isolate a group of HTML elements based on the element\'92s name, such as all the <h1> or all the <p>.\
syntax eg. [element name] \
element selector code structure eg. \cf3 h1 \{\
					   color: blue;\
					   \}\
\cf4 (all the h1 elements would be coloured blue)\cf0 \
						\
